$lang['How do you convert a Hexadecimal to a Decimal?'] = 'Ndenge nini okoki kobongola Hexadécimal na Décimal?';
$lang['When converting hexadecimal to decimal, the first step is to divide the hex number by 16. This will give you the base number. The second step is to divide each digit of the hex number by 16 and write down the results. Finally, add up all of the numbers that were just calculated.'] = 'Ntango ozali kobongola hexadécimal na décimale, likambo ya liboso ezali ya kokabola motango ya hexadecimal na 16. Yango ekopesa yo motango ya base. Likambo ya mibale ezali ya kokabola chiffre mokomoko ya motángo ya hex na 16 mpe kokoma ba résultats. Na nsuka, bakisa mituya nyonso oyo euti kotángama.';
$lang['For example, if someone wants to convert 9F7A to decimal, they would first divide 9F7A by 16 which equals 6051. Then they would divide each digit of 6051 by 16 which equals 381. Lastly, they would add up 381 + 381 + 381 which equals 1144. Therefore, 9F7A in decimal is equal to 1144'] = 'Na ndakisa, soki moto alingi kobongola 9F7A na decimal, akokabola liboso 9F7A na 16 oyo ekokani na 6051. Na nsima, bakokabola chiffre mokomoko ya 6051 na 16 oyo ekokani na 381. Na nsuka, bakobakisa 381 + 381 + 381 oyo ekokani 1144. Na yango, 9F7A na décimale ekokani na 1144';
$lang['How do you convert a Decimal to a Hexadecimal?'] = 'Ndenge nini okoki kobongola Décimal na Hexadécimal?';
$lang['Converting decimal to hexadecimal is a simple process, and can be done with a calculator or online converter. In order to convert the number, divide it by 16 and take the remainder. This remainder will then correspond to a hexadecimal digit. For example, if you have the decimal number 234, divide it by 16 and take the remainder: 234 / 16 = 14 R 2. Therefore, in hexadecimal notation, this number would be written as “E2”.'] = 'Kobongola décimale na hexadécimal ezali mosala ya pete, mpe ekoki kosalema na calculateur to na convertisseur en ligne. Mpo na kobongola motángo yango, kabolá yango na 16 mpe zwá oyo etikali. Na nsima, oyo etikali ekoyokana na chiffre hexadécimal. Ndakisa, soki ozali na motango ya décimal 234, kabola yango na 16 mpe zwa oyo etikali : 234 / 16 = 14 R 2. Yango wana, na notation hexadécimal, motango oyo elingaki kokomama lokola « E2 ».';
$lang['There are many tools available online that can help with converting between decimal and hexadecimal numbers. Additionally, most calculators have a built-in function that will allow you to do this conversion very easily. With just a few clicks of the mouse or taps on the keyboard, you’ll be able to change any decimal value into its corresponding hexadecimal equivalent!'] = 'Ezali na bisaleli mingi oyo ezali na Internet oyo ekoki kosalisa mpo na kobongola kati na mituya ya desimale mpe ya hexadécimal. En plus, ba calculateurs mingi ezalaka na fonction intégrée oyo eko permettre yo osala conversion oyo très facilement. Soki obɛti kaka mwa ba cliquage ya souris to obɛti na klaviatware, okozala na likoki ya kobongola motuya nyonso ya décimal na équivalent hexadécimal na yango oyo ekokani na yango!';
$lang['What are the benefits of using a Hexadecimal over a Decimal?'] = 'Matomba nini ya kosalela Hexadécimal likolo ya Décimal?';
$lang['The hexadecimal, or base-16, system was designed to emulate some of the same properties as the decimal system. In other words, it was created to make things easier for us humans. The number 423 has 16 digits instead of 10 digits available in a decimal system. This is because hexadecimal uses a base of 16 symbols instead of 10. After F, the order begins again with 0 and so on and so forth until we get to 15 which is notated as F.'] = 'Système hexadécimal, to base-16, esalemaki mpo na komekola mwa bizaleli ndenge moko na système decimal. Na maloba mosusu, ekelamaki mpo na kosala ete makambo ezala pɛtɛɛ mpo na biso bato. Motango 423 ezali na ba chiffres 16 na esika ya ba chiffres 10 oyo ezali na système décimal. Yango ezali mpo ete hexadécimal esalelaka base ya bilembo 16 na esika ya 10. Sima ya F, ordre ebandi lisusu na 0 mpe bongo na bongo mpe bongo na bongo kino tokokóma na 15 oyo ekomami na bilembo F.';
$lang['Hexadecimal encoding reduces the number of digits by a factor of eight when compared to the decimal system. Additionally, hexadecimal numbers have an information density that is twice as high as decimal numbers do. So, why should you bother learning this funky little numbering scheme? Because it can make your life easier! When working with digital systems or data transmission, using hex will save you time and energy when decoding cryptic messages or data streams.'] = 'Encodage hexadécimal ekitisaka motango ya ba chiffres na facteur mwambe soki tokokanisi yango na système décimal. Longola yango, mituya ya hexadécimal ezali na densité ya nsango oyo eleki mbala mibale mituya ya desimale. Bongo, mpo na nini osengeli komitungisa mpo na koyekola mwa mayele oyo ya kotánga banimero ya funky? Mpo ekoki kosala ete bomoi na yo ezala pɛtɛɛ! Ntango ozali kosala na ba systèmes numériques to transmission ya ba données, kosalela hex ekobatela yo temps mpe énergie tango ozali ko décoder ba messages cryptiques to ba flux ya ba données.';
$lang['What are the benefits of using a Decimal over a Hexadecimal?'] = 'Matomba nini ezali na kosalela Décimal koleka Hexadécimal?';
$lang['When it comes to binary coding, Hexadecimal is more efficient because it reduces 8 digits to 2. Additionally, Hex provides a greater degree of information density and higher accuracy in numbers than binary does. This is due to the fact that Hex uses 16 symbols instead of just two like binary. Because of this increased efficiency, Hexadecimal is often used when binary coding in computing and digital electronics as well as for computer science applications.'] = 'Soki etali codage binaire, Hexadécimal ezali efficace mingi mpo ekitisaka 8 chiffres na 2. En plus, Hex epesaka degré monene ya densité ya information mpe précision ya likolo na ba nombres koleka binaire. Yango euti na likambo oyo ete Hex esalela bilembo 16 na esika ya kosalela kaka mibale lokola binaire. Na tina ya efficacité oyo emati, Hexadecimal esalelamaka mingi tango ya codage binaire na informatique na électronique numérique ainsi que pona ba applications ya informatique.';
$lang['In addition, Hexadecimal takes up less space than decimal. With only two digits instead of 8 binary digits, Hex numbers represent large numbers much more concisely. This can be very helpful when working with computer systems, as there is less chance for mistakes when typing in hex codes compared to decimal codes which have so many decimal points all over the place!'] = 'En plus, Hexadécimal ezuaka esika moke koleka décimale. Lokola ezali kaka na ba chiffres mibale na esika ya ba chiffres binaire 8, ba nombres Hex ezali komonisa ba chiffres minene na ndenge ya mokuse mingi. Yango ekoki kozala na litomba mingi ntango ozali kosala na ba systèmes informatiques, lokola ezali na chance moke ya mabunga ntango ozali kokoma na ba codes hexagoliques soki tokokanisi yango na ba codes décimaux oyo ezali na ba points décimaux ebele na esika mobimba!';
$lang['What is the range of values that can be represented by a Hexadecimal?'] = 'Range ya ba valeurs oyo ekoki kozala représenté na Hexadécimal ezali nini?';
$lang['A hexadecimal number is a number that uses 16 digits instead of the 10 digits we use in the decimal system. This number system is called base-16, and it helps us to emulate the properties of our familiar decimal system. In hexadecimal, each digit represents a power of 16. The numbers 0 through 9 represent the powers of 1 through 10, while A through F represent the powers of 11 through 15.'] = 'Motango ya hexadécimal ezali motango oyo esalelaka ba chiffres 16 na esika ya ba chiffres 10 oyo tosalelaka na système décimal. Système oyo ya ba nombres babengaka yango base-16, mpe esalisaka biso to imiter ba propriétés ya système décimal oyo tomeseni na yango. Na hexadécimal, chiffre moko na moko ezali komonisa nguya ya 16. Mituya 0 kino 9 ezali komonisa nguya ya 1 kino 10, nzokande A kino F ezali komonisa nguya ya 11 kino 15.';
$lang['Just like in decimal, after 16 symbols have been used in Hexadecimal, the order of numbers starts over again at zero. So, hexadecimal 10 is equal to decimal 16, and hexadecimal 11 is equal to decimal 17. And so on!'] = 'Kaka ndenge moko na décimal, sima ya kosalela bilembo 16 na Hexadécimal, ordre ya ba nombres ebandi lisusu na zéro. Na yango, hexadécimal 10 ekokani na décimale 16, mpe hexadécimal 11 ekokani na décimale 17. Mpe bongo na bongo!';
$lang['What is the range of values that can be represented by a Decimal?'] = 'Range ya ba valeurs oyo ekoki kozala représenté na Décimal ezali nini?';
$lang['The Decimal system starts with 10 and goes up to 15. This means that the range of values that can be represented by a decimal number is from 0-9, followed by A-F (10-15).'] = 'Système Décimal ebandi na 10 mpe emati tii na 15. Yango elakisi ete intervalle ya ba valeurs oyo ekoki kozala représenté na nombre décimal ezali kobanda 0-9, elandi na AF (10-15).';
$lang['How do you decode Hexadecimal?'] = 'Ndenge nini okoki ko décoder Hexadécimal?';
$lang['When it comes to decoding Hexadecimal, there are a few things you need to know. First, just like the decimal system, the hexadecimal system has 10 symbols (0-9) that represent numbers. However, in hexadecimal, these digits have values that are twice as large as their counterparts in the decimal system. So, while the number “10” is represented by the symbol “A” in hexadecimal, it would be equal to “10” in the decimal system.'] = 'Soki etali décodage ya Hexadécimal, ezali na mua makambo oyo esengeli oyeba. Ya liboso, kaka ndenge moko na système décimal, système hexadécimal ezali na bilembo 10 (0-9) oyo ezali komonisa mituya. Kasi, na hexadécimal, ba chiffres wana ezali na ba valeurs oyo ezali minene mbala mibale koleka baninga na yango na système decimal. Na yango, atako motángo “10” emonisami na elembo “A” na hexadécimal, ekozala ndenge moko na “10” na système decimal.';
$lang['Similarly, after reaching 9 in Hexadecimal (represented by “F”), we start counting again at 10 (“10”). This pattern continues until we reach 15 (“1F”), at which point we reset back to 0 and begin counting again at 16 (“20”). This might sound confusing at first, but with a little practice, it will become second nature!'] = 'Ndenge moko mpe, nsima ya kokóma na 9 na Hexadécimal (oyo emonisami na “F”), tobandi lisusu kotánga na 10 (“10”). Motindo oyo ekobaka tii tokokóma na 15 (“1F”), na esika yango tozongisaka na 0 mpe tobandi lisusu kotánga na 16 (“20”). Yango ekoki koyokana lokola mobulungano na ebandeli, kasi soki omeseni mwa moke, ekokóma bomoto ya mibale!';
